communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The outbreak, which reportedly started in Lusaka on 8 Nov 2013, remained solitary and was declared officially "resolved" on 1 Apr 2014 (see Zambia's final OIE report of 9 Jul 2014 at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapEventSummary&reportid=15555).

The immediate notification of the said event included the following description of the affected population: "The cases are on commercial and semi-commercial farms rearing exotic pig breeds (mainly landrace, large white, and crosses, etc.). The pigs are housed in permanent buildings and mortalities have involved both young and old." The statistics were: out of 37 117 susceptible swine, there were 189 cases of which 180 died and 4627 were destroyed. No slaughtering was reported. The control measures applied were, according to the report: quarantine, movement control inside the country, screening, and zoning. The epidemiological comment was: epidemiological investigations are ongoing to determine the source of the outbreak and its extent.

No explanation was provided for the destruction of about 12 per cent of the susceptible, exposed population; have only animals with clinical signs been destroyed? Or those of a certain age group?

In view of the current remarks of Zambia's Minister of Agriculture, it will be interesting to obtain, on the one hand, data on the considerations upon which the decision to declare the event resolved were taken earlier this year (2014), and on the other hand, an updated evaluation of Zambia's ASF situation as seen on the ground.

ASF is a viral, OIE listed highly infectious disease of swine; it is not zoonotic. So far, no vaccine has become available. - Mod.AS

Maps of Zambia can be seen at http://www.nmcc.org.zm/images/report_map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2886575,2939. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
